01:37.598 --> 01:41.834
Tangier, it's Morocco.

01:41.835 --> 01:43.936
But from 1923 through 1956, it

01:43.937 --> 01:44.971
was loosely governed by the

01:44.972 --> 01:48.475
major powers, an
international zone.

01:48.476 --> 01:51.378
For years it seemed
everything was permitted.

01:51.379 --> 01:54.914
Nothing was forbidden.

01:54.915 --> 01:58.551
At the northern tip of Africa, a

01:58.552 --> 02:06.552
short ferry hop from Spain,
Tangier was a magnet for

02:07.928 --> 02:09.596
writers, remittance men,
spies, and artists.

02:09.597 --> 02:10.564
If you were a bad boy of your

02:10.565 --> 02:11.565
time, you liked drugs, the kind

02:11.566 --> 02:12.699
of sex that was frowned upon at

02:12.700 --> 02:15.235
home and an affordable lifestyle
set against an exotic

02:15.236 --> 02:23.236
background, Tangier was for you.

02:26.680 --> 02:29.849
Matisse, Genest,
William Burroughs.

02:29.850 --> 02:30.883
Many have come this way, staying

02:30.884 --> 02:34.020
a while or hanging around.

02:34.021 --> 02:37.190
But no one stayed longer or

02:37.191 --> 02:38.658
became more associated with

02:38.659 --> 02:42.929
Tangier than the novelist
and composer Paul Bowles.

02:42.930 --> 02:45.031
In works like "the sheltering

02:45.032 --> 02:46.499
sky" he created a romantic

02:46.500 --> 02:50.337
vision of Tangier that persists

02:50.338 --> 02:51.671
even today, a dream that's

02:51.672 --> 02:56.376
become almost inseparable in the

02:56.377 --> 02:58.945
minds of many from reality.

02:58.946 --> 03:03.616
I'm here to find
that dream city.

03:03.617 --> 03:09.423
The place Burroughs
referred to as "Interzone."

03:10.658 --> 03:18.658
♪

03:27.808 --> 03:29.909
Tangier, like I said, was a city

03:29.910 --> 03:32.011
of ex-pats... people with pasts,

03:32.012 --> 03:33.012
people who simply didn't like

03:33.013 --> 03:35.114
where they were and craved

03:35.115 --> 03:38.751
somewhere and something else.

03:38.752 --> 03:40.387
The grand socco is the gateway

03:40.388 --> 03:42.522
to the Medina where you could

03:42.523 --> 03:49.662
find the Casbah, which
means fortress by the way.

03:49.663 --> 03:51.731
The port is to the east, and

03:51.732 --> 03:52.765
right in the middle of it all,

03:52.766 --> 03:55.302
the petit socco, called the last

03:55.303 --> 04:01.774
stop, the meeting place, the
switchboard of Tangier.

04:01.775 --> 04:03.810
Reasons for settling in Tangier

04:03.811 --> 04:08.481
diverge, but everyone sooner or

04:08.482 --> 04:09.582
later since the beginning of

04:09.583 --> 04:11.684
memory comes to cafe Tingis.

04:11.685 --> 04:12.685
Jonathan Dawson came to this

04:12.686 --> 04:16.789
city over 20 years ago as a

04:16.790 --> 04:18.425
journalist, and he never left.

04:18.426 --> 04:20.427
He lives a life not too distant

04:20.428 --> 04:23.563
from Burroughs' fantasy.

04:23.564 --> 04:25.097
Cake and tea at 4:00 every day

04:25.098 --> 04:27.734
served by his man servant.

04:27.735 --> 04:33.440
He may not have a gazelle,
but a pet rooster will do.

04:33.441 --> 04:36.142
And every day he makes the

04:36.143 --> 04:37.677
rounds of the cafes, seeing all

04:37.678 --> 04:44.016
the old faces, ending up
sooner or later here.

04:44.017 --> 04:45.017
This is the petit socco?

04:45.018 --> 04:46.619
This is the petit socco.

04:46.620 --> 04:48.755
Yes.

04:48.756 --> 04:51.257
It existed in venetian times,

04:51.258 --> 04:53.426
existed in Roman times, in the

04:53.427 --> 04:55.895
Portuguese times and the English

04:55.896 --> 04:56.963
were here for 22 years and then

04:56.964 --> 05:00.099
the international city
until 1956, now here.

05:00.100 --> 05:04.270
This is a very historic
scare, very historic.

05:04.271 --> 05:05.872
As a writer, I've noticed

05:05.873 --> 05:07.840
everybody who comes here to do

05:07.841 --> 05:09.976
an article does
the same article.

05:09.977 --> 05:12.011
It is so damn boring.

05:12.012 --> 05:13.580
They're all the beat generation

05:13.581 --> 05:14.647
and there are lots of other

05:14.648 --> 05:15.682
stories in Morocco apart from

05:15.683 --> 05:18.785
that, but everyone
likes the beats.

05:18.786 --> 05:21.388
Bill Burroughs, Tennessee

05:21.389 --> 05:23.490
Williams, they were all here,

05:23.491 --> 05:26.158
but that's a small part
of the Moroccan history.

05:26.159 --> 05:27.193
That's a 15-year page.

05:27.194 --> 05:29.295
There was a life before
that and a life after that.

05:29.296 --> 05:30.329
You're here.

05:30.330 --> 05:31.864
Yeah.

05:31.865 --> 05:33.900
It was inevitable.

05:33.901 --> 05:36.035
Let's pretend those
guys never came.

05:36.036 --> 05:39.606
What is this place?

05:39.607 --> 05:42.274
The reality is, you can
read the story and live it.

05:42.275 --> 05:42.910
People do come here and try to

05:42.911 --> 05:45.878
live it, but they
don't stay very long.

05:45.879 --> 05:46.946
They smoke a little dope, go to

05:46.947 --> 05:49.015
a cheap hotel and go
home with bedbugs.

05:49.016 --> 05:50.049
And a great story.

05:50.050 --> 05:51.083
And a great story.

05:51.084 --> 05:53.219
The attitude here is different
than other parts of

05:53.220 --> 05:54.754
Morocco.

05:54.755 --> 05:57.457
I think they have a higher

05:57.458 --> 06:00.560
tolerance of tradition of
bad or outrageous behavior.

06:00.561 --> 06:05.231
They have a high tolerance
of mad people, you know?

06:05.232 --> 06:11.971
But Moroccans essentially
are very tolerant people.

06:11.972 --> 06:13.039
They quite like madness as well.

06:13.040 --> 06:15.074
They kind of celebrate
that a bit.

06:15.075 --> 06:15.609
You know?

06:15.609 --> 06:16.577
How Moroccan is Tangier?

06:16.578 --> 06:18.745
It's a Moroccan city
with a European outlook.

06:18.746 --> 06:20.747
You can stand up on the
boulevard and see Spain and

06:20.748 --> 06:22.281
Gibraltar and see all sorts of

06:22.282 --> 06:25.418
people passing through, but
it is a Moroccan city.

06:25.419 --> 06:29.088
I'm 62 years old.

06:29.089 --> 06:30.623
I didn't know international days

06:30.624 --> 06:32.692
which finished in 1956, but at

06:32.693 --> 06:33.760
that time, I think Europeans may

06:33.761 --> 06:35.828
have outnumbered Moroccans
in the center of this city.

06:35.829 --> 06:37.430
It's not the case now.

06:37.431 --> 06:38.431
There's very few Europeans

06:38.432 --> 06:41.734
actually living here full time.

06:41.735 --> 06:44.270
The notion of living a life

06:44.271 --> 06:46.906
apart, of being somewhere else,

06:46.907 --> 06:49.509
there are those who
like that feeling.

06:49.510 --> 06:52.612
I like that feeling.

06:52.613 --> 06:53.646
Then there are those who may

06:53.647 --> 06:54.647
live apart, may live somewhere

06:54.648 --> 06:59.819
else, but they're not
entirely comfortable.

06:59.820 --> 07:01.387
It's the difference annoys
them or is a burden.

07:01.388 --> 07:03.990
It did, and it frustrates them.

07:03.991 --> 07:07.594
Some people have to leave
home to find their home.

07:07.595 --> 07:09.161
I'm one of those people.

07:09.162 --> 07:15.401
Whereas I didn't feel at home in

07:15.402 --> 07:16.435
the country I was born in at

07:16.436 --> 07:17.470
all, but here I feel okay.

07:17.471 --> 07:19.071
I feel very, very happy here.

07:19.072 --> 07:24.243
There is indeed something
special about this place.

07:24.244 --> 07:26.345
Burroughs described the native

07:26.346 --> 07:28.981
quarter of Tangier as a maze of

07:28.982 --> 07:34.821
sunless twisting streets
filled with blind alleys.

07:34.822 --> 07:36.288
Its smell was particularly

07:36.289 --> 07:39.926
notable to him, including a mix

07:39.927 --> 07:44.163
of hashish, seared
meat, and sewage.

07:44.164 --> 07:46.766
Tangier, before anything else,

07:46.767 --> 07:49.368
is essentially a port city,
with all the things that

07:49.369 --> 07:54.507
traditionally come
with port cities.

07:54.508 --> 07:55.542
It's situated at the choke point

07:55.543 --> 08:00.212
between the Atlantic ocean
and the Mediterranean sea.

08:00.213 --> 08:03.315
The Moroccan coast is a rich

08:03.316 --> 08:04.350
fishing ground, and a lot of

08:04.351 --> 08:07.486
people make their
living from the sea.

08:07.487 --> 08:10.089
Onshore they use a method called

08:10.090 --> 08:11.123
sentul fishing, where weighted

08:11.124 --> 08:15.294
nets basically drag fish
across the bottom of the sea.

08:15.295 --> 08:17.630
Some of that fish, the good

08:17.631 --> 08:21.934
stuff anyway, ends up here.

08:21.935 --> 08:23.936
The saveur de Poisson, or

08:23.937 --> 08:26.138
restaurant populare or Popeye's.

08:26.139 --> 08:28.174
The place has a lot of names,

08:28.175 --> 08:29.776
but locals and ex-pats alike who

08:29.777 --> 08:30.843
have been coming here for years

08:30.844 --> 08:35.914
say it has some of the
best tagine in town.

08:35.916 --> 08:37.249
Mohammed, the owner and head

08:37.250 --> 08:39.919
chef, is from the nearby rif

08:39.919 --> 08:41.020
mountains, and he sources a lot

08:41.020 --> 08:42.488
of his stuff, his produce and

08:42.489 --> 08:46.793
his Greens, from there, and
he's real proud of them.

08:46.794 --> 08:48.327
The back room is dedicated to

08:48.328 --> 08:50.396
sorting and drying various herbs

08:50.397 --> 08:51.397
which he blends into a secret

08:51.398 --> 08:56.135
mix that he claims has all
sorts of healthful and

08:56.136 --> 08:58.304
boner-inspiring benefits.

08:58.305 --> 08:59.405
If every dish I have been told

08:59.406 --> 09:02.441
over the years would make me

09:02.442 --> 09:03.475
strong worked, I would have a

09:03.476 --> 09:05.177
permanent pup tent going on

09:05.178 --> 09:07.513
down there, so I take all
that with a grain of salt.

09:07.514 --> 09:11.283
Hi.

09:11.284 --> 09:13.586
Hello.

09:13.587 --> 09:15.688
His son Hassan
delivers the food.

09:15.689 --> 09:19.558
It all starts with fresh olives,

09:19.559 --> 09:20.559
they're in season now.

09:20.560 --> 09:22.729
And roasted wall nuts.

09:22.730 --> 09:24.263
Some warm, very good bread.

09:24.264 --> 09:26.398
Squishy.

09:26.399 --> 09:27.900
And you get this stuff.

09:27.901 --> 09:30.603
Everybody gets it.

09:30.604 --> 09:33.105
A pulpy puree of figs, raisins,

09:33.106 --> 09:36.575
strawberries and full of
Mohammed's potent herbs and

09:36.576 --> 09:39.746
spices, of course.

09:39.747 --> 09:42.314
All night, 24 clock.

09:42.315 --> 09:43.449
Yeah, yeah, I get it.

09:43.450 --> 09:44.917
It's supposed to
make me more manly.

09:44.918 --> 09:45.985
You know what?

09:45.986 --> 09:47.720
I'm eating.

09:47.721 --> 09:50.657
Let's not talk about
that, okay, sunshine?

09:50.658 --> 09:53.826
What is a tagine, anyway?

09:53.827 --> 09:57.229
It's a traditional Moroccan stew

09:57.230 --> 10:00.833
that can include
vegetables, meat, or ship.

10:00.834 --> 10:05.938
Tonight, baby shark, calamari
and monk fish with fresh

10:05.939 --> 10:10.943
mountain shin spinach cooked in

10:10.944 --> 10:15.414
a classic Clay pot that
gives it its name.

10:15.415 --> 10:16.016
The domed top is supposed to

10:16.016 --> 10:16.884
force the condensation back in

10:16.885 --> 10:18.450
to the dish and keep
it moist and tender.

10:18.451 --> 10:18.986
That's delicious.

10:18.987 --> 10:20.019
I think it's the Greens and the

10:20.020 --> 10:22.054
aromatics and the herbs, I
have no idea what they are.

10:22.055 --> 10:23.055
Never had anything like it.

10:23.056 --> 10:25.692
Tangier version
of farm to table.

10:25.693 --> 10:26.193
Hi.

10:26.194 --> 10:28.795
Wow.

10:28.796 --> 10:29.829
When's that?

10:29.830 --> 10:35.301
Thank you.

10:35.302 --> 10:38.971
And a whole turbot, brushed with

10:38.972 --> 10:41.573
olive oil, salt, and pepper and

10:41.574 --> 10:47.279
some coriander, then grilled
perfectly over the coals.

10:47.280 --> 10:49.348
Cuddled up next to the
fish, tiny shark kabobs.

10:49.349 --> 10:50.416
Cute.

10:50.417 --> 10:51.450
Wow, spectacular.

10:51.451 --> 10:53.119
Good value.

10:53.120 --> 10:54.921
All of this for 20 bucks?

10:54.922 --> 10:56.155
Pretty good job on Mr. Fish.

10:56.156 --> 11:00.793
That will teach you.

11:00.794 --> 11:08.794
[ Speaking foreign language ]

11:12.773 --> 11:13.806
He's freaking me out.

11:13.807 --> 11:14.841
It's like that guy with, you

11:14.842 --> 11:19.511
know, you're tripping
and does this to you?

11:19.512 --> 11:22.148
For dessert, strawberries,
pine nuts and honey.

11:22.149 --> 11:24.150
Like the whole meal, it's
eccentric and delicious.

11:24.151 --> 11:25.184
Thank you.

11:25.185 --> 11:31.958
You're welcome.

11:31.959 --> 11:38.330
I haven't had so much fruits
and nuts since Altaban.

11:38.331 --> 11:43.736
I told Mick, I said, Mick,
this is a bad crowd.

11:43.737 --> 11:49.041
But he's like, man, we
can't disappoint the fans.

11:49.042 --> 11:51.611
Ah, memories.

12:03.623 --> 12:09.962
In Tangier, I lived in one
room in the native quarter.

12:09.963 --> 12:12.064
I have not taken a bath in a

12:12.065 --> 12:16.735
year nor changed my clothes or

12:16.736 --> 12:17.770
removed them except to stick a

12:17.771 --> 12:20.940
needle every hour in the fibrous

12:20.941 --> 12:23.675
gray wooden flesh of
termal addiction.

12:23.676 --> 12:28.614
I never cleaned or
dusted the room.

12:28.615 --> 12:34.586
Amputee everyone pul boampule

12:34.587 --> 12:37.857
objections and garbage
piled up to the ceiling.

12:37.858 --> 12:39.458
Light and water long since
turned off for nonpayment.

12:39.459 --> 12:40.427
I did absolutely nothing.

12:40.428 --> 12:42.494
I could look at the end of
my shoe for eight hours.

12:42.495 --> 12:43.562
I was only roused to action when

12:43.563 --> 12:51.103
the hourglass of junk ran out."

12:51.104 --> 12:53.672
The words of William Seward

12:53.673 --> 12:56.308
Burroughs, one of my heroes.

12:56.309 --> 12:58.911
He came to Tangier in 1953,

12:58.912 --> 12:59.946
shortly after shooting his wife

12:59.947 --> 13:03.082
to death in a drunken
accident in Mexico City.

13:03.083 --> 13:08.320
He was a heroin addict, a

13:08.321 --> 13:09.355
homosexual, and an inspiration

13:09.356 --> 13:17.356
to those protohipsters who
became known as the beats.

13:19.732 --> 13:25.404
Burroughs, however,
was not a beat Nick.

13:25.405 --> 13:26.438
He was a somewhat stuffy,

13:26.439 --> 13:27.074
well-dressed St. Louis son of a

13:27.074 --> 13:28.041
good family gone wrong.

13:28.042 --> 13:29.108
He was also to my mind the

13:29.109 --> 13:30.576
greatest writer of the
whole damn bunch.

13:30.577 --> 13:31.544
On the road, you can have it.

13:31.545 --> 13:36.448
His classic "naked
lunch" was written here.

13:36.449 --> 13:39.551
A nonlinear, dark, dry humored

13:39.552 --> 13:40.619
searingly critical and satirical

13:40.620 --> 13:44.256
and profane masterpiece.

13:44.257 --> 13:47.894
Burroughs was apparently high

13:47.895 --> 13:49.761
for much of the process on

13:49.762 --> 13:57.762
heroin or locally available
prescription opiate.

13:58.505 --> 14:00.606
And the daily staple in
many of these parts.

14:00.607 --> 14:01.740
Hashish, keef and maldune.

14:01.741 --> 14:03.775
Hashish is the concentrated THC

14:03.776 --> 14:05.211
resin of the cannabis plant as

14:05.212 --> 14:07.046
well as varying amounts of its

14:07.047 --> 14:07.847
flowers and leaves that have

14:07.848 --> 14:09.381
been separated from the buds and

14:09.382 --> 14:14.320
compressed into sheet
or brick-like form.

14:14.321 --> 14:15.821
Keif is the part of the plant

14:15.822 --> 14:17.389
containing only the strongest

14:17.390 --> 14:21.027
concentration of
psychoactive ingredients.

14:21.028 --> 14:22.094
Majune is a confection made from

14:22.095 --> 14:28.267
keef, fruits, nuts,
chocolate and honey.

14:28.268 --> 14:30.369
I was, of course, fascinated by

14:30.370 --> 14:33.472
this product since reading about

14:33.473 --> 14:34.506
it and inquired of some local

14:34.507 --> 14:37.743
contacts who shall
necessarily go unnamed.

14:37.744 --> 14:39.745
How was it made?

14:39.746 --> 14:43.415
This is what I wanted to know.

14:43.416 --> 14:49.621
They were kind enough
to demonstrate.

14:49.622 --> 14:51.690
Keef is first chopped into fine

14:51.691 --> 14:53.292
granules and slowly added to

14:53.293 --> 14:55.962
melted butter and chocolate
over a low heat.

14:55.963 --> 14:57.296
You toast it and release the

14:57.297 --> 15:01.600
psychotropic goodies within.

15:01.601 --> 15:05.471
While the binder element is slow

15:05.472 --> 15:08.174
cooking in the pan, a
combination of spices are

15:08.175 --> 15:10.042
blended with ka shoes, almonds,

15:10.043 --> 15:12.744
walnuts, and dried fruit.

15:12.745 --> 15:13.812
This will be the framework to

15:13.813 --> 15:17.950
suspend the THC-laden
goodness in the next step.

15:17.951 --> 15:20.086
The cannabis-laced butter

15:20.087 --> 15:21.087
chocolate is added along with

15:21.088 --> 15:25.924
plenty of honey to bind
together all the ingredients.

15:25.925 --> 15:33.925
Then mix.

15:37.737 --> 15:39.271
Last, you roll the entirety of

15:39.272 --> 15:41.407
the mixture into a ball and

15:41.408 --> 15:48.147
either refrigerate
or dig right in.

15:48.148 --> 15:50.216
Of course, network standards and

15:50.217 --> 15:51.817
practices prohibit me from even

15:51.818 --> 15:53.385
tasting this delicious and

15:53.386 --> 15:54.920
reportedly mind-altering treat.

15:54.921 --> 15:58.024
I'm guessing, anyway.

15:58.025 --> 16:00.126
So until I see Chris, John and

16:00.127 --> 16:01.227
wolf doing bong riffs in "the

16:01.228 --> 16:02.761
situation room," I will, of

16:02.762 --> 16:04.330
course, abide by these rules

16:04.331 --> 16:09.001
because that's the
kind of guy I am.

16:09.002 --> 16:11.037
There's one particular cafe in

16:11.038 --> 16:12.104
the heart of the Kasbah that's

16:12.105 --> 16:13.639
drawn in foreign dignitaries,

16:13.640 --> 16:16.242
rock stars, aristocrats and

16:16.243 --> 16:20.846
artists since it opened
its doors in 1943.

16:20.847 --> 16:26.052
Cafe Baba.

16:26.053 --> 16:31.257
Sweet mint tea in a thick
slow-moving haze of smoke.

16:31.258 --> 16:33.859
It smells like my
dorm room 1972.

16:33.860 --> 16:36.462
Good evening, hello.

16:36.463 --> 16:41.667
This is George Bajalia and

16:41.668 --> 16:43.235
Zeneb, and I should say right

