Others in the room, however,
well, don't give me that

17:07.727 --> 17:08.727
innocent look, you young punks.

17:08.728 --> 17:11.297
I know somebody in here
is smoking reefer.

17:11.298 --> 17:12.798
How stoned are people here?

17:12.799 --> 17:15.934
We can ask, just ask.

17:15.935 --> 17:19.037
You're not getting
totally ripped here?

17:19.038 --> 17:19.638
No.

17:19.640 --> 17:22.241
It's a functional
part of daily life.

17:22.242 --> 17:23.809
For a long time, the rest of the

17:23.810 --> 17:26.944
country and the government

17:26.945 --> 17:28.480
didn't really like
Tangier a whole lot.

17:28.481 --> 17:29.548
It was seedy.

17:29.549 --> 17:32.184
There were foreigners
who came here and...

17:32.185 --> 17:33.185
It makes money.

17:33.186 --> 17:34.786
He sees it as a future
economic super power as I

17:34.787 --> 17:38.324
understand it.

17:38.325 --> 17:40.592
He's talk uging condos,
boutique hotels.

17:40.593 --> 17:42.561
That is good for bad?

17:42.562 --> 17:45.664
For Moroccans, it's work, but

17:45.665 --> 17:47.233
of course ex-pats want to keep

17:47.234 --> 17:49.868
Tangier like they
know it before.

17:49.869 --> 17:51.370
I mean, this cafe is very

17:51.371 --> 17:52.371
similar to the way it was, but

17:52.372 --> 17:53.405
there's a TV right there.

17:53.406 --> 17:54.473
Flat screen.

17:54.474 --> 17:55.541
That's why people come here.

17:55.542 --> 17:57.576
They come to watch soccer games.

17:57.577 --> 18:01.280
You can well imagine the
American guy who's lived in

18:01.281 --> 18:03.315
Tangier for 30 years.

18:03.316 --> 18:06.452
He comes in, there's a flat
screen TV on the wall.

18:06.453 --> 18:10.122
He's like... what?

18:10.123 --> 18:11.157
You've ruined the authenticity

18:11.158 --> 18:13.825
and the integrity, but the

18:13.826 --> 18:15.294
Moroccan guy at the next table

18:15.295 --> 18:16.995
is, like, wait a minute,

18:16.996 --> 18:18.897
asshole, you have a
flat screen TV at home.

18:18.898 --> 18:19.898
I want one, too.

18:19.899 --> 18:21.967
What is wrong with that?

18:21.968 --> 18:25.103
There are people here who

18:25.104 --> 18:26.205
probably have never heard of...

18:26.206 --> 18:27.206
If you follow that, there's no

18:27.207 --> 18:30.809
progression, no
progress, no change.

18:30.810 --> 18:35.314
The thing about cafe Baba,

18:35.315 --> 18:36.315
just sitting here, taking in the

18:36.316 --> 18:38.950
atmosphere, you begin to
appreciate the place.

18:38.951 --> 18:42.020
There's something
different happening here.

18:42.021 --> 18:45.224
Contact high, whoa, I'm hungry.

18:45.225 --> 18:45.858
Wait until the Spanish tortilla

18:45.859 --> 18:52.431
dude across the street
opens for business.

18:52.432 --> 18:56.702
This is Abdileh.

18:56.703 --> 18:59.738
He specializes in making one

18:59.739 --> 19:02.441
thing, and he make it is well.

19:02.442 --> 19:03.509
He makes an omelet.

19:03.510 --> 19:04.510
It's like a Spanish tortilla.

19:04.511 --> 19:05.511
But like stonier.

19:05.512 --> 19:07.346
The potatoes are boiled, diced,

19:07.347 --> 19:08.614
mixed with beaten eggs and

19:08.615 --> 19:10.749
cooked in a cast iron skillet.

19:10.750 --> 19:11.351
Oh, yeah.

19:11.352 --> 19:12.352
The eggs.

19:12.353 --> 19:14.052
The egg man.

19:14.053 --> 19:14.954
I am me and we are you and where

19:14.955 --> 19:19.658
is my omelet, dude,
because I am hungry.

19:19.659 --> 19:22.728
One, two, three?

19:22.729 --> 19:24.296
Abdileh is waiting for you

19:24.297 --> 19:26.365
when you come stumbling
out of cafe Baba.

19:26.366 --> 19:28.534
Coincidence or not?

19:28.535 --> 19:30.536
You be the judge.

19:30.537 --> 19:31.603
Ketchup and mayonnaise.

19:31.604 --> 19:33.138
Everything.

19:33.139 --> 19:34.706
Ketchup and mayonnaise?

19:34.707 --> 19:35.741
Sure.

19:35.742 --> 19:38.377
Why not?

19:38.378 --> 19:39.411
Condiment options I will be hard

19:39.412 --> 19:47.412
pressed to turn down at
this precise moment anyway.

19:51.958 --> 19:54.493
A lot of mayonnaise.

19:54.494 --> 19:55.494
Hmm.

19:55.495 --> 19:56.562
Dude, that's awesome.

19:56.563 --> 19:59.799
I'll have 12 more.

20:00.633 --> 20:03.570
♪

20:12.745 --> 20:15.080
Paul Bowles lived in Tangier

20:15.081 --> 20:16.715
for over 50 years, and Sherry

20:16.716 --> 20:18.884
nutting was part of his inner

20:18.885 --> 20:21.052
circle near the end of his life.

20:21.053 --> 20:23.655
She was his friend, record
keeper of sorts, and

20:23.656 --> 20:24.690
photographer.

20:24.691 --> 20:26.191
You arrived when?

20:26.192 --> 20:30.362
I came in the '70s, but
went down to Marrakesh.

20:30.363 --> 20:31.397
In '86, I wrote a letter to Paul

20:31.398 --> 20:32.431
Bowles and said I had to meet

20:32.432 --> 20:33.565
him and take his picture.

20:33.566 --> 20:35.033
He wrote back and
said, come and visit.

20:35.034 --> 20:36.602
Well, I never left.

20:36.603 --> 20:37.703
A lot of people came here to

20:37.704 --> 20:40.772
live that dream or
to live that life.

20:40.773 --> 20:44.009
Has the reality come to resemble

20:44.010 --> 20:49.415
his perception of the reality?

20:49.416 --> 20:54.219
The Tangier I see
is Paul Bowles.

20:54.220 --> 20:55.321
I still see it.

20:55.322 --> 20:55.788
I still feel it.

20:55.789 --> 20:56.888
You can still find the magic.

20:56.889 --> 20:57.889
The market or souk in Tangier

20:57.890 --> 20:58.990
is one of the best in Morocco.

20:58.991 --> 21:02.060
The vendors are still
pretty impressive.

21:02.061 --> 21:03.094
Wander the markets long enough

21:03.095 --> 21:05.063
and you're sure to stumble
across the unexpected.

21:05.064 --> 21:06.164
Hooves?

21:06.165 --> 21:07.165
Sure.

21:07.166 --> 21:09.768
How about a lamb's head?

21:09.769 --> 21:14.373
Here nothing goes to waste.

21:14.374 --> 21:18.677
Charbroiled to crispy burnt

21:18.678 --> 21:23.148
perfection, it's served
on a crusty lunch bread.

21:23.149 --> 21:30.956
Not so adventurous?

21:30.957 --> 21:33.525
The grand socco's indoor market

21:33.526 --> 21:36.261
offers a variety of smoked,
cured and fresh meat.

21:36.262 --> 21:37.229
Smells good in here.

21:37.229 --> 21:37.764
The stuff looks good.

21:37.765 --> 21:39.365
I've heard this
cheese is amazing.

21:39.366 --> 21:40.432
It's good, yeah.

21:40.433 --> 21:41.433
Could I have one?

21:41.434 --> 21:42.501
A Berber favorite, fresh goat

21:42.502 --> 21:43.502
cheese wrapped in palm leaves.

21:43.503 --> 21:46.171
Yeah, they're
beautiful, aren't they?

21:46.172 --> 21:49.307
It's good.

21:49.308 --> 21:50.876
[ Speaking foreign language ]

21:50.877 --> 21:53.445
A little cheese, a little

21:53.446 --> 22:00.386
flat bread, the perfect
Moroccan breakfast to go.

22:00.387 --> 22:07.125
We're headed into the Ja Bala

22:07.126 --> 22:08.193
foothills in the mountain range

22:08.194 --> 22:09.761
about 80 kilometers of Tangier

22:09.762 --> 22:11.296
to a place called Jajouka.

22:11.297 --> 22:12.864
The village is home to the

22:12.865 --> 22:14.433
people of the Al Sharif tribe,

22:14.434 --> 22:20.706
which loosely translated
means the saintly people.

22:20.707 --> 22:25.377
Jajouka is also home to one
of Morocco's better-known

22:25.378 --> 22:28.447
musicians, Bashir attar.

22:28.448 --> 22:29.848
Jazz and rock and roll musicians

22:29.849 --> 22:31.316
have traveled from all over the

22:31.317 --> 22:35.220
world to Jajouka
to meet this guy.

22:35.221 --> 22:37.322
He's part of a lineage of master

22:37.323 --> 22:41.092
musicians all from this
small mountain village.

22:41.093 --> 22:45.130
♪

22:45.131 --> 22:50.335
Famously dubbed as a
4,000-year-old rock band by

22:50.336 --> 22:55.040
William Burroughs, Bashir, his

22:55.041 --> 22:58.243
son, and these musicians

22:58.244 --> 22:59.078
maintain one of the oldest still

22:59.079 --> 23:01.146
living musical
traditions on earth.

23:01.147 --> 23:07.385
♪

23:07.386 --> 23:11.056
We're invited for dinner.

23:11.057 --> 23:14.693
It's family style, of course,

23:14.694 --> 23:16.762
beginning with braywine, like a

23:16.763 --> 23:19.998
kefta pocket, hand formed

23:19.999 --> 23:21.767
envelopes of dough filled with

23:21.768 --> 23:23.602
seasoned beef baked until golden

23:23.603 --> 23:26.672
and then crisped in oil.

23:26.673 --> 23:30.341
I'm good for now well, one more.

23:30.342 --> 23:33.311
Uh-oh, here we go.

23:33.312 --> 23:37.683
The main event,
tajine of chicken.

23:37.684 --> 23:38.717
Welcome, Tony.

23:38.718 --> 23:42.320
Thank you.

23:42.321 --> 23:49.127
Just gorgeous.

23:49.128 --> 23:51.229
First, chopped onions, garlic,

23:51.230 --> 23:59.230
parsley and turmeric are
blended with olive oil.

23:59.438 --> 24:02.541
The bird is generously
coated and stuffed.

24:02.542 --> 24:03.575
Then after simmering in a touch

24:03.576 --> 24:05.110
of olive oil and water, it is

24:05.111 --> 24:06.945
fried until crispy, served with

24:06.946 --> 24:11.382
roasted almonds and olives,
paprika, and ginger.

24:11.383 --> 24:12.417
Nice.

24:12.418 --> 24:13.451
He smells the food.

24:13.452 --> 24:16.087
Like anywhere else in the
Arab world, eating with your

24:16.088 --> 24:18.156
hands, always the right one, is

24:18.157 --> 24:21.793
proper dining etiquette.

24:21.794 --> 24:28.033
This is spinach.

24:28.034 --> 24:29.067
It's wild spinach.

24:29.068 --> 24:31.169
It grows in the mountains?

24:31.170 --> 24:34.139
Yeah.

24:34.140 --> 24:39.545
Chopped mountain spinach

24:39.546 --> 24:41.112
garlic, cilantro, hot and black

24:41.113 --> 24:43.715
peppers finished with
lemon and olive oil.

24:43.716 --> 24:48.453
That's delicious.

24:48.454 --> 24:49.988
I heard you are the greatest

24:49.989 --> 24:51.557
taste for food in
the world, man.

24:51.558 --> 24:52.591
I love good food.

24:52.592 --> 24:53.592
This is good.

24:53.593 --> 24:56.695
Yeah.

24:56.696 --> 24:58.764
After dinner some fruit, some

24:58.765 --> 25:05.003
mint tea, and let
the music begin.

25:05.004 --> 25:06.037
For centuries, the master

25:06.038 --> 25:08.674
musicians of Jajouka have been

25:08.675 --> 25:11.242
the musical choice of the royal

25:11.243 --> 25:13.344
families of Morocco, excused by

25:13.345 --> 25:14.379
the country's rulers from manual

25:14.380 --> 25:20.553
labor to devote themselves
to musical training.

25:22.354 --> 25:30.354
♪

25:43.442 --> 25:48.747
♪

25:48.748 --> 25:53.151
Their powerful style of Sufi

25:53.152 --> 25:55.687
transmusic has inspired many

25:55.688 --> 25:56.722
music seekers, including most

25:56.723 --> 25:57.756
notably perhaps Paul Bowles, who

25:57.757 --> 25:59.357
wrote about them and recorded

25:59.358 --> 26:02.460
them, and spread the word.

26:02.461 --> 26:05.530
Brian Jones was here and
recorded "the pipes of pan at

26:05.531 --> 26:12.370
Jajouka" with these musicians.

26:12.371 --> 26:14.005
The word spread and the master

26:14.006 --> 26:15.907
musicians have ended up being

26:15.908 --> 26:19.878
featured on albums by Annette

26:19.879 --> 26:27.753
Coleman and the rolling stones.

26:27.754 --> 26:30.321
For years, if you were a rock

26:30.322 --> 26:34.459
god, you had to come here, dig

26:34.460 --> 26:36.027
the crazy percussion, strings,

26:36.028 --> 26:38.129
and pipes that took
you to another place.

26:38.130 --> 26:43.835
It's intricate,
hypnotic, beautiful.

26:43.836 --> 26:46.939
If you're in the right frame
of mind, mesmerizing.

26:57.416 --> 26:59.484
Anyone who comes to Tangier

26:59.485 --> 27:03.689
inevitably ends up lost in
the old part of the city.

27:03.690 --> 27:06.257
The Medina is just what
you want it to be.

27:06.258 --> 27:08.359
The ancient world residing just

27:08.360 --> 27:14.666
next to and around the new one.

27:14.667 --> 27:16.735
You can walk around inside the

27:16.736 --> 27:21.807
movie in your head, play the

27:21.808 --> 27:24.710
bogey character you never were,

27:24.711 --> 27:25.744
all against an all too willing,

27:25.745 --> 27:26.778
all too genuine backdrop.

27:26.779 --> 27:28.246
Ordinarily just about the last

27:28.247 --> 27:31.382
thing in the world I would
be interested in doing is

27:31.383 --> 27:32.918
antiquing, but buried in the

27:32.919 --> 27:40.919
network of twisting narrow
streets of the old city is

27:46.532 --> 27:49.434
boutique Majid
owned by this man.

27:49.435 --> 27:51.970
And he's one interesting guy.

27:51.971 --> 27:53.004
Thank you.

27:53.005 --> 27:54.039
Come in.

27:54.040 --> 27:54.673
When he was a little kid back

27:54.673 --> 27:55.607
in the '60s, Majid left his

27:55.608 --> 27:57.175
hometown of fez and came here

27:57.176 --> 27:59.244
where he would earn money
emptying ashtrays at wild

27:59.245 --> 28:03.715
parties being thrown
here by wealthy ex-pats.

28:03.716 --> 28:05.483
He saw what these people would

28:05.484 --> 28:06.617
buy for themselves and how they

28:06.618 --> 28:07.719
would decorate their homes, and

28:07.720 --> 28:10.588
he started to look around for

28:10.589 --> 28:15.293
himself, scoring, then
reselling art and antiques.

28:15.294 --> 28:16.294
Wow.

28:16.295 --> 28:22.968
It became something
of an obsession.

28:22.969 --> 28:26.604
Now his artifacts from Morocco

28:26.605 --> 28:27.239
and north Africa are bought by

28:27.239 --> 28:28.174
collectors all over the world.

28:28.175 --> 28:29.207
Jewelry and old doors.

28:29.208 --> 28:31.309
Wow, these are
incredibly beautiful.

28:31.310 --> 28:35.981
Tell me about that.

28:35.982 --> 28:39.084
Amber, coral, shells.

28:39.085 --> 28:39.651
These used to be currency.

28:39.652 --> 28:41.219
These shells.

28:41.220 --> 28:43.254
How old is this?

28:43.255 --> 28:44.489
Early '20s.

28:44.490 --> 28:46.391
The Amber is millions
of years old.

28:46.392 --> 28:49.527
How much are you selling it for?

28:49.528 --> 28:51.096
By weight.

28:51.097 --> 28:56.267
Quite heavy piece
this one, 429 grams.

28:56.268 --> 28:58.369
So it comes like 42,000
so that's how much in

28:58.370 --> 28:59.404
dollars?

28:59.405 --> 29:03.041
Almost $5,000.

29:03.042 --> 29:03.542
About $5,000.

29:03.543 --> 29:04.543
Almost.

29:04.544 --> 29:06.077
Should we look at another floor?

29:06.078 --> 29:11.316
Oh, yes, follow me.

29:11.317 --> 29:17.288
There's a nice collection
of things from the Sahara.

29:17.289 --> 29:18.323
So you travel a lot?

29:18.324 --> 29:21.459
Not like you.

29:21.460 --> 29:25.096
Oh, this is for pounding...
Yes, this is from the Gon

29:25.097 --> 29:26.131
tribe.

29:26.132 --> 29:27.232
From Mali.

29:27.233 --> 29:28.766
How much will this
sell for do you think?

29:28.767 --> 29:29.835
Around $300.

29:29.836 --> 29:30.836
Really?

29:30.837 --> 29:32.971
For this?

29:32.972 --> 29:35.540
That's very reasonable.

29:35.541 --> 29:36.574
I'll be buying that.

29:36.575 --> 29:38.676
That's going to
be an old friend.

29:38.677 --> 29:39.710
Also memory.

29:39.711 --> 29:44.415
Also memory of Tangier as well.

29:44.416 --> 29:49.787
Majid suggests lunch at
Andalus, a locals only place

29:49.788 --> 29:54.692
nearby.

29:54.693 --> 29:55.760
As a Moroccan, so many people

29:55.761 --> 29:56.794
come with a romantic notion of a

29:56.795 --> 29:58.363
Tangier they read
about in books.

29:58.364 --> 30:01.432
Do people have a
realistic expectation?

30:01.433 --> 30:02.901
Are they looking for Morocco or

30:02.902 --> 30:07.338
are they looking
for this phantasm?

30:07.339 --> 30:08.373
It is a phantasm.

30:08.374 --> 30:09.440
It is.

30:09.441 --> 30:10.441
When you get here, you know

30:10.442 --> 30:11.576
Morocco, you feel that you are

30:11.577 --> 30:13.644
in Morocco but you are not.

30:13.645 --> 30:16.314
There's a lot of Mediterranean
attached to this town.

30:16.315 --> 30:17.815
Also the history, people hear

30:17.816 --> 30:19.985
story about Tangier that it

30:19.986 --> 30:21.987
was... when I first came in the

30:21.988 --> 30:24.655
'60s, everybody said
that you came late.

30:24.656 --> 30:27.192
Right.

30:27.193 --> 30:29.260
Now I'm saying the same
thing as the young now.

30:29.261 --> 30:30.761
They come and they
saw wow, I say...

30:30.762 --> 30:34.432
What was better
about those days?

30:34.433 --> 30:36.001
Well, for me at that time I

30:36.002 --> 30:39.137
was young, and it was the boom

30:39.138 --> 30:42.240
of hippies, and it
was a destination.

30:42.241 --> 30:44.842
You know, cafe Baba, meet Bob

30:44.843 --> 30:47.445
Dylan, and the parties
was going on.

30:47.446 --> 30:50.048
I miss these kind of parties.

30:50.049 --> 30:51.616
People fly from everywhere to

30:51.617 --> 30:55.786
the party, and they make
the whole town move.

30:55.787 --> 30:58.356
Blue and white party, white and

30:58.357 --> 31:01.559
gold party, hat party,
you know, it's amazing.

31:01.560 --> 31:04.695
You see people coming in with

31:04.696 --> 31:05.664
amazing hats, like a cage with a

31:05.665 --> 31:09.400
bird, extravagant
hats, you know.

31:09.401 --> 31:10.036
They put so much energy and time

31:10.037 --> 31:11.970
into the parties, you know?

31:11.971 --> 31:19.710
Look at... now, that looks good.

31:19.711 --> 31:21.346
Tomatoes brushed with local

31:21.347 --> 31:24.983
olive oil, garlic and coriander.

31:24.984 --> 31:26.051
Liver kabobs, beef liver to be

31:26.052 --> 31:29.154
exact, grilled over charcoal.

31:29.155 --> 31:31.222
That looks very nice.

31:31.223 --> 31:33.959
For fish, a bit of swordfish and

31:33.960 --> 31:37.828
and some orange roughy.

31:37.829 --> 31:39.397
That is just beautiful.

31:39.398 --> 31:40.966
How do you like the tomato?

31:40.967 --> 31:45.203
The swordfish is amazing.

31:45.204 --> 31:46.204
So how else have things changed?

31:46.205 --> 31:48.773
You saw how many tourists
there was today?

31:48.774 --> 31:50.875
They were in a hurry.

31:50.876 --> 31:53.478
If they come to the shop,
even try to avoid your eye

31:53.479 --> 31:55.546
contact.

31:55.547 --> 31:57.648
They afraid if you get my eye

31:57.649 --> 32:01.352
contact, I'm going
to rip you off or...

32:01.353 --> 32:03.554
Or make you buy something
that they don't want?

32:03.555 --> 32:04.555
I don't know.

32:04.556 --> 32:05.091
I don't know.

32:05.092 --> 32:06.092
Do they buy?

32:06.093 --> 32:07.125
They don't even say hello.

32:07.126 --> 32:08.893
They don't buy?

32:08.894 --> 32:09.561
Of course.

32:09.562 --> 32:12.897
We call them penguin.

32:12.898 --> 32:15.766
They have short hands that
don't get into the pockets.

32:15.767 --> 32:17.669
I'm just kidding.

32:44.496 --> 32:46.564
When Tangier was Interzone

32:46.565 --> 32:48.133
back in the day, it seemed to

32:48.134 --> 32:49.167
some I'm sure as if the ex-pats

32:49.168 --> 32:51.302
outnumbered the locals.

32:51.303 --> 32:53.304
That was never true, but you

32:53.305 --> 32:55.406
certainly could live a life

32:55.407 --> 32:59.144
apart, make your own world
within the existing one.

32:59.145 --> 33:03.014
Reinvent yourself and live

33:03.015 --> 33:08.553
entirely within a universe
of your own creation.

33:08.554 --> 33:12.690
Far from the grand socco is
a 14-acre estate owned by

33:12.691 --> 33:14.225
Christopher Gibbs, a well-known

33:14.226 --> 33:17.395
dealer of antiques
and longtime ex-pat.

33:17.396 --> 33:20.465
Today, he's having
a garden party.

33:20.466 --> 33:23.601
Who's coming?

33:23.602 --> 33:25.136
Jonathan you know.

33:25.137 --> 33:26.171
Maggie Dean is from Scotland.

33:26.172 --> 33:34.045
She's been living here
for more than a decade.

33:34.046 --> 33:37.882
GP, a Frenchman who has a
hind in a lot of businesses.

33:37.883 --> 33:41.219
Including a cafe in the Kasbah.

33:41.220 --> 33:42.887
Years living here, unknown.

33:42.888 --> 33:43.988
An American, she's been here

33:43.989 --> 33:46.491
forever, led many lives, I
gather, and occasionally

33:46.492 --> 33:50.295
translates books from
magrabbi to English.

33:50.296 --> 33:52.730
And the dashing and mysterious

33:52.731 --> 33:54.599
baron, an artist from Chile who

33:54.600 --> 33:56.667
has been living and working in

33:56.668 --> 33:58.603
the Kasbah since a hasty exit

33:58.604 --> 34:06.604
from Puerto Rico for reasons
never fully explained.

34:10.116 --> 34:17.388
On the menu, bastilla, a meat or

34:17.389 --> 34:19.989
often pigeon pie, as traditional
Moroccan as it gets.

34:19.991 --> 34:25.196
Today made by Gibbs' full-time

34:25.197 --> 34:26.731
cooks, jamilla and Fatima.

34:26.732 --> 34:27.764
It's chicken slow-cooked, pulled

34:27.766 --> 34:30.368
or shredded and folded
into an egg mixture.

34:30.369 --> 34:32.437
Cooked in a reduced
stock from the boil.

34:32.438 --> 34:36.107
This is layered with blanched

34:36.108 --> 34:39.277
almonds, powdered
sugar, and cinnamon.

34:39.277 --> 34:42.413
The whole lot is wrapped
in a crepe-like dough.

34:42.414 --> 34:45.014
After baking to a golden

34:45.016 --> 34:46.583
crispiness, the final touch is a

34:46.585 --> 34:49.654
dusting of even more
cinnamon and sugar.

34:49.655 --> 34:51.789
It's got a sweet savory thing

34:51.790 --> 34:56.994
going on, and it's quite tasty.

34:56.995 --> 34:59.597
If you get nervous when you

34:59.598 --> 35:03.268
go in a room and you touch the

35:03.269 --> 35:04.302
light switch and the lights

35:04.303 --> 35:12.009
don't come on, you shouldn't
be in this country.

35:12.010 --> 35:12.844
I came here first in 1958.

35:12.845 --> 35:13.978
When it was quite different.

35:13.979 --> 35:15.446
Everyone wore native dress, but

35:15.447 --> 35:18.549
Islam still the throbbing
motor of life here.

35:18.550 --> 35:22.820
I have a very tender feelings
from Morocco and the

35:22.821 --> 35:24.522
friendliness and the courtesy of

35:24.523 --> 35:30.495
the people and its children.

35:30.496 --> 35:33.331
It's bonjour.

35:33.332 --> 35:41.332
[ Speaking foreign language ]

35:44.443 --> 35:45.344
I always feel welcomed here.

35:45.345 --> 35:46.444
I never consider it's mine.

35:46.445 --> 35:47.578
It's theirs and they've allowed

35:47.579 --> 35:48.180
me to feel here in a nice way.

35:48.180 --> 35:48.714
I feel recognition.

35:48.715 --> 35:49.880
They know who I am.

35:49.881 --> 35:52.149
They know who I am.

35:52.150 --> 35:54.419
There is a side by side

35:54.420 --> 35:58.088
aspect to life here
that's very unusual.

35:58.089 --> 35:59.824
Very unusual here.

35:59.825 --> 36:03.494
It's mostly you can do whatever

36:03.495 --> 36:06.063
you want if you do it
with good manners.

36:06.064 --> 36:07.765
It is a station of the cross

36:07.766 --> 36:10.901
for, you know, bad
boys of culture.

36:10.902 --> 36:12.303
I mean, Rambo.

36:12.304 --> 36:14.305
Iggy pop.

36:14.306 --> 36:16.274
The stones.

36:16.275 --> 36:18.309
Burroughs writes and came
here to be a writer.

36:18.310 --> 36:21.412
He was a junkie before
he was a writer.

36:21.413 --> 36:24.549
As so many of us were.

36:24.550 --> 36:25.384
A place to think of yourself

36:25.385 --> 36:27.117
as a writer you would come here

36:27.118 --> 36:28.152
and somehow working within
a romantic tradition.

36:28.153 --> 36:29.387
Yes.

36:29.388 --> 36:33.924
Burroughs said right up
front, writer to me lounged

36:33.925 --> 36:35.626
around in a smoking jacket or a

36:35.627 --> 36:42.267
caftan and smoking littered
with sleeping boys.

36:42.268 --> 36:43.101
Yes.

36:43.101 --> 36:43.669
Or girls.

36:43.670 --> 36:46.237
To what extent did that world

36:46.238 --> 36:46.838
exist and to what extent was

36:46.838 --> 36:47.473
that world created by the people

36:47.474 --> 36:52.777
that showed up with
that expectation?

36:52.778 --> 36:54.745
Since Bill departed, yep,

36:54.746 --> 36:57.315
dear, wonderful, marvelous man,

36:57.316 --> 36:58.749
he's gone, it's tame now.

36:58.750 --> 36:59.618
It is tame.

36:59.619 --> 37:02.720
Well, he was... genteel now.

37:02.721 --> 37:04.722
He was the very
opposite of genteel.

37:04.723 --> 37:07.258
He was an outlaw
of every society.

37:07.259 --> 37:10.395
My husband knew him very well

37:10.396 --> 37:12.129
and he was saying that I cured

37:12.130 --> 37:12.698
him of being a drug addict.

37:12.699 --> 37:14.399
I said how?

37:14.400 --> 37:20.070
He said, I turned him
into an alcoholic.

37:20.071 --> 37:21.806
Who smokes hashish
at this table?

37:21.807 --> 37:22.308
Please raise your hand.

37:22.309 --> 37:28.913
Is the camera on?

37:28.914 --> 37:35.453
Put your hand up, Bianca.

37:35.454 --> 37:36.788
♪

37:49.134 --> 37:53.971
It's my last night in
Tangier and I'm headed out.

37:53.972 --> 37:55.373
Thank you, yes.

37:55.374 --> 37:56.841
Most cities in the Islamic

37:56.842 --> 37:58.809
world, getting a beer
can be difficult.

37:58.810 --> 38:00.244
Not here.

38:00.245 --> 38:01.646
As long as you're outside the

38:01.647 --> 38:03.948
Medina, nearly anything goes.

38:03.949 --> 38:07.051
Tangier reverts to
its libertine past.

38:07.052 --> 38:10.488
Here, western influences
become very apparent.

38:10.489 --> 38:18.489
♪

38:26.738 --> 38:28.473
Any night of the week is a good

38:28.474 --> 38:31.676
night for young Moroccons
to take to the streets.

38:31.677 --> 38:34.445
He's from a generation of

38:34.446 --> 38:37.281
Moroccans far removed
from the Burroughser era.

38:37.282 --> 38:40.117
He's invited me out
for a casual snack.

38:40.118 --> 38:44.689
Tuna, eggs and a
healthy wad of Mayo.

38:44.690 --> 38:48.359
French fries within
the sandwich.

38:48.360 --> 38:50.361
This is delicious.

38:50.362 --> 38:52.363
By the way.

38:52.364 --> 38:54.632
The bread here is very good.

38:54.633 --> 38:58.335
You work in magazine journalist?

38:58.336 --> 39:01.205
Yes.

39:01.206 --> 39:04.575
I'm not a journalist but I own

39:04.576 --> 39:08.579
an urban magazine here in

39:08.580 --> 39:11.115
Tangier to inform Moroccans we

39:11.116 --> 39:16.887
are living in a place
that's pretty special.

39:16.888 --> 39:18.889
It is not a place for Burroughs

39:18.890 --> 39:23.728
or Paul Bowles or other
people came to Tangier.

39:23.729 --> 39:24.329
The city has something which

39:24.330 --> 39:26.564
makes it different
from other cities.

39:26.565 --> 39:27.998
What about young artists,

39:27.999 --> 39:29.434
young writers, young musicians?

39:29.435 --> 39:31.402
Do they come here expecting this

39:31.403 --> 39:35.105
romantic Paul Bowles
wonderland of the '50s?

39:35.106 --> 39:36.507
Some were.

39:36.508 --> 39:38.476
Some weren't.

39:38.477 --> 39:40.210
Too bohemian.

39:40.211 --> 39:41.912
Too bohemian?

39:41.913 --> 39:43.914
Yeah.

39:43.915 --> 39:47.618
They thought that coming
and being an artist...

39:47.619 --> 39:49.019
Is going to be enough?

39:49.020 --> 39:50.755
Is going to be enough.

39:50.756 --> 39:53.290
Today it is not enough.

39:53.291 --> 39:55.560
Most of them pack their bags.

39:55.561 --> 39:57.562
Right.

39:57.563 --> 40:00.130
Today we have so many
investments going on here in

40:00.131 --> 40:01.032
Tangier thanks to our king.

40:01.032 --> 40:01.833
Investors are here.

40:01.834 --> 40:03.834
Tourists are attracted.

40:03.835 --> 40:05.536
But the most important part of

40:05.537 --> 40:09.807
it is we should keep the old
parts of the city intact.

40:09.808 --> 40:11.509
The Kasbah, the Medina.

40:11.510 --> 40:13.511
That's what's hard to do because

40:13.512 --> 40:17.815
when you have a European
purchasing power coming over

40:17.816 --> 40:18.750
here to Tangier... they
come like we come.

40:18.750 --> 40:19.518
We embrace it.

40:19.519 --> 40:20.951
Other people want to come.

40:20.952 --> 40:22.119
And then we throw up.

40:22.120 --> 40:26.657
We'll, will Tangier's
unique character survive?

40:26.658 --> 40:28.926
I hope so.

40:28.927 --> 40:36.927
I really hope so.

40:44.843 --> 40:47.444
Tangier is Morocco.

40:47.445 --> 40:49.379
Always was Morocco.

40:49.380 --> 40:53.083
And recently the country's
leadership seems to have

40:53.084 --> 40:55.653
embraced it.

40:55.654 --> 40:57.655
In all its ill reputed glory.

40:57.656 --> 41:00.791
The days of predatory poets in

41:00.792 --> 41:02.226
search of literary inspiration

41:02.227 --> 41:05.896
and young flesh are
probably over for good.

41:05.897 --> 41:08.165
Hippies can just as easily get

41:08.166 --> 41:12.369
their bong rips in
Portland or Peoria.

41:12.370 --> 41:14.739
But the good stuff, the real

41:14.740 --> 41:16.140
good stuff, the sounds and

41:16.141 --> 41:18.475
smells and the look of Tangier,

41:18.476 --> 41:21.045
what you see and hear when you

41:21.046 --> 41:23.013
lean out the window and take it

41:23.014 --> 41:27.352
all in, that's here to stay.

